{# Jagarôth}

* Jagarôth 
* Phonology
   
   *Jagarôth vowels*
   *and* /English/ words with illustrative vowel sounds

** digraphs and diphones
*** digraphs: sh zh th dh ch kh
    Digraphs in transliterated Jagarôth represent a single consonantal phoneme (these 
    digraphs have "h" as their 2nd component). 
*** diphones: q, x, j
    Jagarôth uses three diphones in transliteration:
    *q* = /kw/
    *x* = /ks/
    *j* = /dzh/

** pure vowels
   a e i o u â ê î ô û
*** a :: bat
*** e :: bet
*** i :: bit
*** o :: boat
*** u :: put~putt
*** â :: khan
*** ê :: bait
*** î :: beet
*** ô :: bought
*** û :: boot

** diphthongs
   ai ei oi au eu
*** ai :: bite
*** ei :: bait
*** oi :: boy
*** au :: bout
*** eu :: butte

** consonants
***  p b m f v t d n s 
***  z sh zh th dh r l
***  h kh k g h w y 
***  ch j 

*** initial clusters
    there are three 3-phoneme initial consonant clusters:
    skr skl str
**** p b t d k g w th dh sk st f v + r
**** p b k g w th s sk f v + l
**** p t k + s
**** s + p t k n m 

*** final clusters
**** nasal + p b t d 
**** r + p b t d k g n m s z sh zh th dh
**** l + p b t d k g n m th
**** diphthong + most consonants (consonants that represent a single phoneme)
**** p t k + s
**** s + p t k 

** Phonotactics (Syllabic structures)
   - Content words begin and end consonantally.
   - Particles and morphemes (non-content words) do not have to follow
     that rule.
   - Many content words do not contain a consonant cluster.
   - A content word may either begin or end with a permitted cluster.
     Only one cluster is permitted per content word. Many content
     words do not contain a cluster. 
   - Non-permitted clusters obviously occur at the inner boundaries of
     compound words. 
   - Content words have one two or three syllables in the nominative,
     which is unmarked. 
   - Long vowels and diphthongs take a stress.
   - Compound words are usually stressed on the first syllable of the
     second component.
   - Most often a content word will be stressed on the initial
     syllable unless the word contains a long vowel or diphthong, in
     which case that vowel is stressed.
   - If a word contains two long vowels, the first receives the stress
     accent. 
   - A content word will not contain two diphthongs. 

** Phonotactics (Stress accent)

